* RANDOM ACCESS MEMORY MAP
	Welcome to Random  access memory map!  This environment	 gives you the
direct access to any portion of  the 1-Mb address space of your  computer. You
can search memory for ASCII or hex strings, edit memory in ASCII or hex  mode,
paste portions  of memory  into Multi-Edit  windows or  write them  to disk in
binary mode. You can also get information on various DOS memory structures, as
memory control blocks, TSRs, device drivers, DOS drive parameter blocks.
	The first time you invoke RAM map row 2 of the screen looks  typically
like this:

^Bâ–‘0000:0000â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘Chainâ–‘toâ–‘â–‘38E7:00CEâ–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘Absoluteâ–‘00000â–‘â–‘â–‘â–‘^b

	The segment:offset indicator to the left is the address where the  RAM
display starts. The "Chain to" indicator  gives the value of DWORD pointer  at
segment:offset; you can actually  go to the location  it points to if  you hit
<F8>  --  Chain  key.  Currently  it  points  to  the INT 0 -- divide error --
handler.  This  interrupt  is  intercepted  by  Multi-Edit,  so  you will find
yourself somewhere inside the Multi-Edit  code. Press <CtrlHome> to return  to
0000:0000.
	You  cannot  fail  to  notice  that  two bytes at locations 0:0440 and
0:046C are rapidly changing their values.  The former is time until motor  off
and the latter is  the least significant byte  of counter of 55ms  ticks since
CPU reset; it actually occupies four bytes (0:046C - 0:0470).

			       ^BNavigation Keys^b

	^B<UP>,<DN>,<PGUP>,<PGDN>^b -- Browse through the memory within  currently
set segment.
	^B<HOME>^b -- Go to segment:0000.
	^B0-9A-F^b -- Set hex address to start memory display. The arrow (^B^b) on
row 1 shows where you are; use ^B<LF>^b and ^B<RT>^b to move the arrow.
	^B<GREY+>, <GREY->^b -- Increase/decrease the starting offset.
	^B<Ctrl> or  <Ms>^b --  Move the  current character  indicator
around the screen. The hex value  of that character is displayed on  the lower
status bar.
	^B<Alt>,  <AltHOME>,  <AltEND>^b  --  Move  the  lower status bar. The
display is squeezed between the upper bar,  which is always on row 2, and  the
lower bar, which  you can move  up or down,  changing the number  of displayed
rows.

