PASTE PASTE CURRENT SCREEN INTO MULTI-EDIT WINDOW
	The portion of RAM that is currently displayed is either inserted into
current window at cursor  position or you can  choose to insert it  into a new
window.
HEXINS HEX INSERT
	Type hex values  of characters you  wish to insert  at segment:offset.
Press ^B<CR>^b to confirm or ^B<ESC>^b to abort operation.
EDIT ASCII EDITING OF A STRING
	You are currently editing in  text mode the string of  memory starting
at current character and ending at the right border of the display window. See
@ME.HLP^PROMPTS[prompts].
GOTOMK GO TO MARKED POSITION IN RAM
	This @ME.HLP^VARMENU[variable length menu] allows you to go to any of the previously
marked positions in RAM. Use ^B<F5>^b to mark positions.
SEARCH ASCII SEARCH
	Input  the  search  string  and  press  ^B<CR>^b. Use ^B<CtrlF6>^b to continue
searching. Please  note that  while you  are in  the "active  zone" of memory,
where the execution is currently under way, the found string may get instantly
overwritten by  some other  stuff --  you will  probably not  have the time to
notice it.
HEXSRC HEX SEARCH
	Type hex  values of  characters you  wish to  look for.  Press ^B<CR>^b to
confirm or ^B<ESC>^b to abort operation.
INTVEC LOCATE INTERRUPT VECTOR
	The interrupt vector for interrupt  n occupies four bytes starting  at
address  4*n.  This  service  performs  this  multuplication for you. Type the
interrupt  number  (in  hex)  and  press  ^B<CR>^b.  You will find yourself at the
desired  location,  the  "Chain  to"  indicator  giving you the address of the
handler.
BINWRI WRITING A PORTION OF MEMORY TO A DISK FILE
	You can save  the specified number  of bytes from  your RAM to  a disk
file. Supply the  filename, the bytes  count in hex  or dec (you  must specify
which value is to be used), and select ^B[Write]^b to perform the operation.
LOAD LOAD FILE INTO MEMORY
	Specify the file to be loaded in free memory above Multi-Edit. To make
use of this function, Multi-Edit must have been started with /An option with n
large enough to receive the file. See @ME.HLP^CMDLINE[Command-line options].